ts had long been in crisis, before Steven D. Lavine led it to financial prosperity and international acclaim. Today, CalArts is the cradle of many Academy Award and Pulitzer Prize winners, of Mellon and Guggenheim Fellows – a hotspot of American creativity. In personal conversations with Jörn Jacob Rohwer, Lavine tells his life story for the first time, talking about cultural politics, philanthropy, the avant-garde and Los Angeles at the centre of his life. Spurred on by self-doubts and a desire to learn from failure, he proves to be a sensitive thinker, visionary and transatlantic mediator between the worlds of art, politics and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aBiografie. 4aCalArts. 4aFehlerkultur. 4aFührungsstil. 4aGespräch. 4aJ.J. Rohwer. 4aJudentum. 4aKunst. 4aKunstschule. 4aSteven D. Lavine. 4aThomas Mann House. 4aTransatlantische Beziehungen. 4aWalt Disney.  aArt.  aBiography.  aCalArts.  aConversations.  aCrisis.  aFailure.  aFoundraising.  aInterview.  aJudaism.  aJörn Jacob Rohwer.  aLavine.  aLos Angeles.  aRohwer.  aSteven D. Lavine.  aThomas Mann House.  aUS culture.  aWalt Disney.  aart school.  aresilience.  atransatlantic relations.0 cprintz978342298155340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978342298724140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783422987241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783422987241.jpg  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK